<blockquote>Dear Prof. {<a href="http://www.lapaul.org/">Paul</a>,<a href="http://www.consc.net/">Chalmers</a>,<a href="http://www.tedsider.org/">Sider</a>},<div><br /></div><div>Are you able to recommend any conferences in metaphysics?<br /></div><div><br /></div><div><br /></div><div>chad</div><div></div><div><br /></div><div><hr /></div><div><br /></div><div>I suggest you attend the Pacific APA this year and go to the metaphysics talks and anything else of interest.</div><div><br /><a href="http://www.apa-pacific.org/current/">http://www.apa-pacific.org/current/</a></div><div><br /></div><div>Laurie<br /></div><div><br /></div><div></div><div><div><hr /></div><span><span><br />the best thing to go to would probably be a meeting of theamerican philosophical association (the pacific division isbest but all three are OK) -- lots on every topic, includingmetaphysics, kant, etc.<br /><br />djc.<br /></span></span><div><br /></div><div><div><hr /><br /></div></div></div><div>Hi Chad,<br /><br />I don't have any particular all-metaphysics conference to recommend; but the annual American Philosophical Association divisional conferences (Eastern, Central, Pacific) often have some good metaphysics talks. The APA website is here:<br /><br /><a class="moz-txt-link-freetext" href="http://www.apaonline.org/">http://www.apaonline.org/</a><br /><br />Best,<br />TS</div><div></div></blockquote><div>Well that answers that! So what do you think, should I spend $800 and go to the<a href="http://www.apaonline.org/divisions/eastern/2008annualmeeting.aspx">Eastern</a>division conference in Philadelphia Dec. 27-31? From what I understand Vancouver would take a lot more to get to.</div><div class="blogger-post-footer"><img width='1' height='1' src='https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/36506138-5257450786785475025?l=blag.whit537.org' alt='' /></div>
